<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-01-11T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-01-11T18:00:00-05:00" n="484" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">841.857 L 97/126½a: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                    <persName type="to">Colonel E. M. House</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-01-11T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 11, 1916—6 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>No. 2. <hi rend="italic">Lusitania</hi> case progressing. Satisfactory
                            settlement probable. Germany apparently believes if case settled it will
                            leave only matters with Great Britain unsettled and some action will be
                            necessary.</p>
                        <closer>[File copy not signed]</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>